02:02.667 --> 02:03.728
government. At the time, it was organized a little 
bit differently from the way it is run now, and I'll

02:05.671 --> 02:11.639
get that in just a second. Secondly was the 
Memorial Student Center that Wayne Stark ran and

02:11.659 --> 02:19.270
provided that opportunity for kids to lead. And 
then there was Corps of Cadets, of course, which

02:20.161 --> 02:24.446
had always been a part of the routine. And then 
there was the Residence Halls Association, which

02:25.347 --> 02:34.278
was an organization basically made up of kids 
living on campus.

02:35.941 --> 02:49.257
Within that MSC hierarchy, there were other 
activities in which students could participate,

02:35.941 --> 02:49.257
whether it was a political forum or SCONA or, you 
know, whatever, the opus, all of the various, very

02:50.198 --> 03:14.026
many positive, worldly kinds of things that I 
think Wayne Stark should be given a great deal of

02:50.198 --> 03:14.026
credit for bringing to our university, and also 
for giving kids an opportunity to participate,

02:50.198 --> 03:14.026
and of course, thanks to the folks who gave money to 
support it, like the Wiley Lecture Series, for

02:50.198 --> 03:14.026
example, but to bring those kinds of things to 
campus. At the time, student government was

03:16.029 --> 03:19.733
organized in a fashion such that The president, 
that each of the officers of, we really sort of had a

03:20.827 --> 03:25.331
mixed bag. It really wasn't a separated 
government in terms of the traditional

03:25.351 --> 03:29.334
government sense. People ran for president, 
people ran for one of the various vice presidents

03:31.496 --> 03:38.502
that were available. One was academic affairs, 
one was finance, one was rules and regs, one was

03:38.522 --> 03:47.190
external affairs, and there was another one, and I 
cannot remember what they said. Oh, student

03:47.210 --> 03:49.652
services.

03:50.797 --> 03:55.363
Each of those people ran independently. But 
ultimately, when those people were elected, they

03:55.383 --> 04:00.989
were automatically members of the Senate. So each 
of those vice presidents served as members of the

04:02.371 --> 04:13.825
legislative voting body, with the exception of 
me, the president, who had a ex officio role but

04:02.371 --> 04:13.825
could not vote. But there was this thing called the 
executive committee. And the executive

04:16.108 --> 04:20.213
committee was made up of these five vice 
presidents. none of whom ran together on a ticket,

04:20.480 --> 04:41.310
and this president, who did not have a vote, and the 
speaker, who was the elected individual from the

04:20.480 --> 04:41.310
Senate body, and the MSC president served as a 
member of the executive committee. What I did when

04:41.530 --> 04:48.360
I became president was I included the court 
commander as a member of the executive committee

04:48.931 --> 04:53.061
and expanded it in that fashion. Now, by the same 
token, I served as a member of the MSC council,

04:53.502 --> 05:01.320
which was the governing body of the, so there was 
sort of like a swap out that occurred, but there was

05:01.520 --> 05:11.415
A lot of, in fact, everybody who, ironically, the 
guy who served as MSC president at that time and

05:01.520 --> 05:11.415
other members of his council, the guy who was core 
commander at that time, were also members of the

05:01.520 --> 05:11.415
Senate, too. So we generally loaded it up, and so 
you were engaged in two or three different

05:11.495 --> 05:21.250
activities, and there was a great... A unifying, 
not a dividing up. That is true. Now we still had

05:26.369 --> 05:30.814
the, we still had the, you know, normal core 
non-reg kind of a deal. Of course, percentage of

05:30.854 --> 05:33.778
the student body was declining. And we still had 
that. In fact, my race for student body president,

05:37.301 --> 05:49.515
I ran against a guy, a guy from the Corps of Cadets, 
and another guy who was a non-reg like myself.

05:50.086 --> 05:51.147
won it on the first ballot. We didn't have to worry 
about a runoff, which was kind of nice. Describe

05:54.371 --> 05:57.214
your campaign. My campaign, the guy who was sort of 
like my campaign chairman was a guy from Kenya who

05:57.234 --> 06:07.186
had previously been vice president of academic 
affairs, and his name was Rajesh Kent. And Raj

06:08.027 --> 06:14.575
served as my campaign chairman, for whatever that 
meant. And at that time, we had a limit on spending

06:14.673 --> 06:21.843
associated with the campaigns of $100. And that 
