07:31.555 --> 07:47.420
sort of lucked out in the sense that I had this 
constituency there that still there were tons of

07:31.555 --> 07:47.420
kids who came from agricultural backgrounds or 
who lived in towns that I'd been in their, you know,

07:31.555 --> 07:47.420
Temple High School, speaking to a high school 
assembly or whatever from my FFA days. And there

07:47.500 --> 07:50.705
were a lot of folks there that I knew or who knew of 
me. And so I kind of got a cadre of individuals

07:52.087 --> 07:59.318
together like, would you please go talk for me at 
this collegiate FFA meeting or would you go talk

07:52.087 --> 07:59.318
for me at this animal sciences, science, 
engineering society meeting and that was the

07:59.686 --> 08:07.437
summit substance of it. It was pretty quick. Do you 
think that all of your student activities had any

08:08.899 --> 08:14.266
effect on your grade point ratio? No, none. I kid 
the kids now because they talk about the reason

08:17.852 --> 08:25.222
it's taking five and a half, six years to get out of 
school. I'm on your side on that one. Because

08:27.850 --> 08:32.998
there's just so many student activities in which 
they can be involved in. And their involvement in

08:33.018 --> 08:36.924
them, they just don't have time. So therefore, 
they take 12 hours a semester. There was not a

08:41.171 --> 08:48.142
single semester during my very short time when we 
started counting up months at Texas A&M. There was

08:48.162 --> 08:52.449
not a single semester where I took less than a full 
load. And I considered a full load at least 16

08:52.469 --> 08:55.714
hours. My last semester as an undergraduate, I 
took 22 hours and got a 4-0. And the same was the case

09:02.043 --> 09:16.137
with my one semester in graduate school, where I 
took 12 hours, which is a full load from a graduate

09:02.043 --> 09:16.137
student perspective. And I managed to balance all 
of that with the seemingly interminable meetings

09:16.157 --> 09:24.165
that arose as a result of my activities as a student 
leader. At the time, too, there were a lot of other

09:28.608 --> 09:30.451
roles. It wasn't just going to a Senate meeting 
every other week, or it wasn't going to an

09:31.012 --> 09:39.906
executive committee meeting every Sunday night, 
but it was also doing the MSC Council stuff. And

09:41.047 --> 09:49.140
various and sundry ones of us, because of the 
leadership roles we had, were student

09:41.047 --> 09:49.140
representatives, voting student 
representatives, in fact. on a number of the

09:49.373 --> 09:51.095
university committees. For example, I served as a 
member of the academic council. Our vice

09:55.641 --> 10:00.627
president from rules and regs served on the rules 
and regs committee for the university. I also

10:01.007 --> 10:02.549
served on the athletic council. So there were a 
number of other activities that were sort of

10:02.609 --> 10:11.481
automatic that came as a result of the leadership 
roles that we occupied. But in the final analysis,

10:11.561 --> 10:16.767
the impact that they had on my grades was kind of 
zero. Let's see. Back to the student routine. What

10:19.462 --> 10:22.446
was your normal dress for class? What did you 
normally wear to class? My normal dress for class

10:24.189 --> 10:35.785
was blue jeans and even a no collared or a sometimes 
collared shirt. I wore boots a lot.

10:40.451 --> 10:42.815
I wore tennis a lot. There were days that my dress 
was different because of the fact that I might have

10:49.280 --> 10:55.086
other activities to do during the day that require 
a coat and tie. For example, some luncheon or some

10:55.106 --> 10:59.771
speech or representing a student body in some 
capacity. But that was more toward my last year on

10:59.791 --> 11:02.434
campus. Otherwise, it was pretty 
student-oriented. Of course, in the summer and a

11:06.378 --> 11:14.967
half that I went to summer school, it was shorts and 
t-shirts kind of a deal. Throughout all this, too,

11:16.280 --> 11:18.663
I was also involved with singing cadets. And so 
there were some times when that required my dress

11:18.683 --> 11:25.852
to be different. Let's do the singing cadets. Bob 
Boone was a conductor. Again, a very, very weird

11:29.957 --> 11:34.122
experience for me. I auditioned for the singing 
cadets in the fall of 1973 when I finally started my

11:34.342 --> 11:44.835
freshman year in earnest and was a bufo, which name 
given to a first-year member of the same cadet,

11:45.203 --> 11:50.588
which is a term that comes from the comic opera. 
And, you know, you had to wear a key, a wooden key,

11:52.330 --> 11:58.716
and you had to go get signatures and, you know, drop 
handles, look out. In fact, this was probably the

11:58.736 --> 12:11.008
closest to the Corps in terms of some of the 
traditions associated with the Corps that I got

11:58.736 --> 12:11.008
was because of my Senate cadet involvement, which 
the Senate cadets had sort of appropriated. And

12:11.427 --> 12:19.858
there were several members, I guess at the time 
probably 15 or 20% of the guys were also in the Corps

12:11.427 --> 12:19.858
of Cadets. And so that sort of worked real well. But 
